<h2>Common Questions About Elder Law & Estate Planning</h2>

<h3>1. How can Medicaid planning help protect my assets when applying for long-term care?</h3>
<p>Medicaid planning is essential for individuals who anticipate needing long-term care, such as nursing home services, while wanting to preserve their hard-earned assets. Without proper planning, Medicaid’s strict eligibility rules may force you to spend down your savings before qualifying for benefits. Our experienced attorneys help you navigate complex Medicaid rules by implementing strategies like asset transfers, trusts, and spend-down plans that comply with state and federal laws. This proactive approach maximizes your chances of qualifying for Medicaid while safeguarding as much of your estate as possible for your loved ones.</p>

<h3>2. What steps should I take if I suspect nursing home abuse or neglect?</h3>
<p>If you or a loved one is experiencing nursing home abuse or neglect, immediate action is crucial. Abuse can take many forms, including physical harm, emotional mistreatment, or inadequate care. Document any signs or symptoms, notify the facility’s management, and contact an elder law attorney who can investigate and advocate on your behalf. At Scales Elder Law, we work diligently to hold negligent parties accountable, pursue compensation for victims, and ensure the safety and dignity of your loved ones moving forward.</p>

<h3>3. Why is it important to have a will and trusts in place as part of estate planning?</h3>
<p>Having a well-drafted will and trusts is fundamental to ensuring your wishes are honored and your estate is handled efficiently. A will establishes how your assets will be distributed and names guardians for minor children, while trusts can provide additional benefits such as avoiding probate, reducing estate taxes, and protecting assets from creditors or Medicaid spend-down requirements. Our attorneys tailor estate plans to meet your unique family and financial situation, providing peace of mind that your legacy will be preserved according to your intentions.</p>